data.sampled:

Let set G be the set of all gold and set M be the set of all metals. Then the first statement implies that G is a subset of M, i.e. G ⊆ M. The second statement implies that there exists a subset of M, say B, such that B consists of only black metals, and B is not empty. 

Therefore, there exists an element in G, say g, that is also in M (since G ⊆ M). And since some metals in M are black (i.e. there exists an element in B that is also in M), then g must also be in B. Hence, we can conclude that some gold is black.

Therefore, we can conclude that there is an eagle that belongs to both E and B (because all eagles are birds) and also belongs to P (because some birds are predators). Thus, we can say that "some eagles are predators".

Let Q be the set of flowers that fade quickly. 

Since "some flowers fade quickly" is true, we have Q ≠ ∅.

Since R ⊆ F, we know that all elements in R are also in F. Therefore, there exists an element y in R such that y ∈ F and y = x.
